 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · Simultaneous Linear Equations",
   "html": "<p><b>Elimination:</b> add/subtract multiples of the equations to remove one variable. <b>Substitution:</b> solve one equation for a variable and substitute. <b>Graphical:</b> intersect the two lines.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Solve $x + y = 7$, $x - y = 3$.",
     "a": "Add: $2x = 10 \\Rightarrow x = 5$. Then $y = 7 - 5 = 2$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Linear & Quadratic Simultaneously",
   "html": "<p>Make one variable the subject in the linear equation, substitute into the quadratic, solve the resulting quadratic.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Solve $y = x+1$ and $y = x^2 - 1$.",
     "a": "$x^2 - 1 = x + 1 \\Rightarrow x^2 - x - 2 = 0 \\Rightarrow (x-2)(x+1)=0$. So $x=2, y=3$ or $x=-1, y=0$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Completing the Square & the Formula",
   "html": "<p>For $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$ with $a\\ne 0$, the roots are given by:</p>$$x = \\dfrac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$$<p>Equivalently, by completing the square:</p>$$a\\left(x+\\dfrac{b}{2a}\\right)^2 = \\dfrac{b^2-4ac}{4a}$$",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Solve $x^2 + 4x - 5 = 0$ by the formula.",
     "a": "$a=1, b=4, c=-5$. $x = \\dfrac{-4\\pm\\sqrt{16+20}}{2} = \\dfrac{-4\\pm 6}{2}$. So $x=1$ or $x=-5$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 4 · Linear Inequalities",
   "html": "<p>Treat like equations, but <b>reverse the inequality</b> when multiplying/dividing by a negative. For two variables, sketch the boundary line (dashed if strict, solid if inclusive), then shade the region satisfying the inequality.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Solve $-3x + 5 < 14$.",
     "a": "$-3x < 9 \\Rightarrow x > -3$ (sign flipped)."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
